This paper is about using a convolutional neural network for semantic modelling of sentences, which is a common topic in the field of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of global pooling and feature graphs, which are techniques commonly used in machine learning and deep learning, leading to cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as likely sub-categories. The paper also mentions the use of dynamic k-max pooling, which is a technique used in neural networks for sequence modelling, leading to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the application of the model to Twitter sentiment prediction, which involves image processing and computer vision techniques, leading to cs.CV (Computer Vision) as a possible sub-category.
